title: Consolidating thread locals in AS::Notifications
body:
I created a registry class which should consolidate a bunch of thread locals being created by the ActiveSupport::Notifications module.

It basically holds a hash of all instrumenters (there's a one to one mapping between notifiers and instrumenters).

title: Delegating the value getter and setters in the ScopeRegistry
body: I'm changing the current implementation of the ``ScopeRegistry`` object so that you don't have to use ``ScopeRegistry.current.value_of`` which is somewhat verbose. Instead, the ``value_of`` and ``set_value_of`` are delegated to ``ScopeRegistry.current``.

title: Hash subtraction (deep_unmerge!)
body:
methods to remove a hash from another hash
- works with deeply nested hash
- works with hash containing arrays

```ruby
{a: {b:"c"}}.deep_unmerge!( {a:{b:"c"}} )                           # => {}
{a: [{c:"d"},{b:"c"}]}.deep_unmerge!({a: [{c:"d"}, {b:"d"}]}) # => {:a=>[{:b=>"c"}]}
```

title: Grouping thread locals in the ActiveRecord scopes
body:
I'm grouping some thread locals under a registry object so that we can try to get the thread locals under control. I've brought the ``current_scope`` and ``ignore_default_scope`` locals together into a single object.

Accesses to these thread locals are now governed through the ``ScopeRegistry`` object.

title: Correctly parse bigint defaults in PostgreSQL
body:
In Postgres, if you have a bigint column with a default value, ActiveRecord would fail to parse to default value correctly and would ignore it. The value coming out of the schema select statement was a typecasted value such as "(0)::bigint". No check was made for such a typecasted value in the default extraction code.

The main consequence of the bug (and how I discovered it) is through schema dumping. A test case is included that covers this issue. Let me know if a test closer to the root cause is required.

title: Fixes skipping object callback filters
body:
This allows you to skip callbacks that are defined by objects, e.g. for
`ActionController`:

    skip_after_filter MySpecialFilter

Previously this didn't work due to a bug in how Rails compared callbacks
in `Callback#matches?`. When a callback is compiled, if it's an object
filter (i.e. not a method, proc, etc.), `Callback` now defines a method on
`@klass` that is derived from the class name rather than `@callback_id`.
So, when `skip_callback` tries to find the appropriate callback to
remove, `Callback` can regenerate the method name for the filter
object and return the correct value for `Callback#matches?`.
